.SH NAME
alarm-postinstall \- set up the client after package installation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B alarm-postinstall [-n|--network PATTERN] [-p|--password STRING] [-c|--central IPSLUG] [-a|--addusers] [-y|--yes]

.SH DESCRIPTION
alarm-postinstall configures the most important bits in order to attach the client to a central node and register local users to the alarm node.
If runs interactively for any missing but required options.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP 
\fB\-a\fP,\fB\-\-addusers\fP
Adds all local users to the group alarm. 
.TP 
\fB\-y\fP,\fB\-\-yes\fP
Selects the suggested network if none is given 

.SH ATTRIBUTES
.TP 
\fB\-n\fP,\fB\-\-network\fP PATTERN
PATTERN is the first three octets of a node IP. At this point subnet masks are not yet supported. The PATTERN has to end with a dot, e.g. '192.168.0.'.
.TP 
\fB\-p\fP,\fB\-\-password\fP STRING
is the password for user alarm on the given central node
.TP 
\fB\-c\fP,\fB\-\-central\fP IPSLUG
Usually, the last octet of the IP of the central node, e.g. 9 for 192.168.0.9, if '192.168.0.' is the provided network. If you have several central nodes
on different networks, provide the full IP here.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR alarm-client (8).

